BA Boeing cut the production rate of the 737 MAX from 52 a month to 42 a month to manage its accumulation Barclays aerospace analyst David Strauss estimates Boeing is about 140 deliveries behind its original 737 MAX 2019 schedule and has accumulated about 300 planes since the grounding of the fleet Strauss expects 737 MAX deliveries to resume in the fourth quarter consistent with what others on Wall Street expect In an upside scenario Strauss wrote in a Friday research report deliveries could resume in the third quarter and production increases to 57 a month in early 2020That timeline and production rate will be a big focus for Boeing stakeholders in ParisBarrons By Al RootJune 7 2019 1157 am ET
